{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"07e6d1eb-1838-4182-a535-6e13e538eef6","content":"The working directory appears to be empty. A `NullReferenceException` is a **runtime** error in your .NET code, not a CLR hosting/activation issue. CLR activation logs (e.g., from `COREHOST_TRACE`) show framework resolution and assembly loading — they won't reveal the source of a `NullReferenceException`.\n\nHere's how to actually diagnose it:\n\n**1. Check the stack trace** — the exception message should include one. Look for the exact line/method where `null` is dereferenced.\n\n**2. Enable detailed logging at startup:**\n```csharp\ntry {\n    // your startup code\n} catch (NullReferenceException ex) {\n    Console.WriteLine(ex.ToString()); // full stack trace\n}\n```\n\n**3. Common startup NRE causes:**\n- Missing configuration/appsettings (e.g., `IConfiguration` returning `null`)\n- Unregistered dependency injection services\n- Null database connection strings\n- Accessing `HttpContext` too early\n\n**To help you further, could you share:**\n- The full exception stack trace?\n- Your startup/`Program.cs` code?\n- Any relevant config files?\n\nDrop those files here and I'll pinpoint the bug.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"c847a122-262a-4f8e-964f-e95e864b9014","outputTokens":292,"requestId":"A0CE:39B23B:85E482:A5DBCD:6A013243"},"id":"c514095c-ca03-4479-9116-fead86dd0a41","timestamp":"2026-05-11T01:35:07.360Z","parentId":"bd96cf2e-25b2-407e-9d77-a1f179a1f9e8"}
